article.description: Zydrunas Ilgauskas had 29 points and seven blocks to lead the Cleveland Cavaliers to a 111-104 victory over the Denver Nuggets, who wasted their best offensive showing of the season.
article.headline: Ilgauskas, Wagner send Cavs for fifth win this season
article.linkText: Ilgauskas piles up 29 points, seven swats to beat Nuggets
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Cavaliers coach John Lucas jumped in the air, pounded the scorer's table with his left hand and screamed loudly. Then, for effect, he did it again.
Ilgauskas

Lucas' outburst in the closing minutes didn't hurt the Cavs. They were doing enough damage all by themselves. Carlos Boozer's three-point play with 10.6 seconds left bailed out Cleveland, which couldn't put away the slumping Denver Nuggets in the final minutes of a 111-104 win Saturday night. Zydrunas Ilgauskas and rookie Dajuan Wagner scored 29 points apiece for the Cavs, who won for just the fourth time at home and fifth time this season. "We kind of forgot what it feels like to win,'' said Ricky Davis, who capped a high-scoring week with 27 points. "It feels good.'' James Posey had 21 for the Nuggets, who dropped their fourth straight and have lost nine of 10. Cleveland led 108-100 with 2:44 left after Davis hit a fadeaway jumper from 15 feet. But the Cavs had four turnovers and missed two shots on their next six possessions to let Denver hang around. After Boozer threw a pass directly to one of the Nuggets, Lucas bounced up the sidelined and slammed the scorer's table and screamed, "Damn, Booze'' in frustration. "I was a little upset there,'' Lucas said, looking at his hand. "I'll take a Tylenol and be fine. Feels a lot better with a win. It wasn't a pretty win, but it was a good one.'' Denver pulled to 108-104 on Rodney White's dunk with 1:42 left, and the Nuggets were still down by just four when they got the ball back with 24 seconds to go. But Davis swatted away Juwan Howard's shot underneath and Darius Miles came out to block White's 3-pointer, starting a fast break that ended with Boozer dunking and getting fouled by Nene Hilario with 10.6 seconds left. "The big thing was the defense at the end,'' Lucas said. "I told them, 'See, we can do it. We can get stops'. Now, we have to apply them for 48 minutes.'' Boozer said as the Cavs mature, they should get better at closing out games. "We need to get better at landing that last punch,'' he said. "We're getting better and better.'' Ilgauskas added eight rebounds and set a career-high with seven blocks, but the Cavs center also matched Ron Harper's team record by making 11 turnovers. "Z almost got a quadruple-double,'' Lucas said. "But in the wrong way.'' Chris Whitney and White had 18 points each and Mark Blount had a career-high 15 for the Nuggets, the league's lowest-scoring team who finally broke 100 for the first time this season. "We were more productive,'' said Nuggets coach Jeff Bzdelik. "But at the same time, Cleveland helped us there.'' Davis opened the fourth with a reverse alley-oop dunk, igniting a 10-2 run that put the Cavs up 99-88 with 8:39 left. However, Cleveland couldn't pull away and continually made bad plays down the stretch to help the Nuggets hang on. Davis, who has had run-ins with Lucas and his teammates this season, averaged 34 points in four games this week. "Maybe I should suspend him again,'' Lucas joked. Ilgauskas' minutes are being closely watched this season by the Cavs, who have him on a limit of 35 per game. The 7-foot-3 center, whose career has been slowed by foot injuries, made the most of the seven minutes he got in the third, scoring 11 points. Coming off a 3-point performance in 32 minutes on Friday night at Boston, Wagner warmed up early, scoring 19 in the first half to help the Cavs take a 61-59 lead at the break.

Game notes
The NBA record for turnovers in a game is 14, shared by John Drew and Jason Kidd. ... Denver has lost seven in a row in Cleveland and 11 of 12. ... Lucas was a Nuggets' assistant for three seasons before getting the Cleveland job. "Things have really changed over there,'' he said before the game. "(James) Posey is like the only one I really know.'' ... The Nuggets entered the game ranked last in the league in six offensive categories. ... Cavs F Tyrone Hill played just eight minutes because of bruised back. ... Harper had 11 turnovers on Feb. 22, 1987.
